HOW WE WORK BEST

When Requirements Are Unclear
	•	Ask specific, clarifying questions.
Prefer “Should this validate on creation?” to guessing.
	•	Present tradeoffs with reasoning.
“A is simpler; B is more flexible. I lean toward A because…”
	•	Push back when something feels off.
“This seems too complex — what if we refactor first?”

When Building
	•	Domain first — pure business logic, zero framework dependencies.
	•	Services orchestrate — coordinate domain objects, never hold business rules.
	•	Routes stay thin — parse → call service → format response.
	•	Think in conversations — each component has a clear role and voice.

When Integrating
	•	Verify extractions (wc -c before/after) to catch truncation.
	•	Test immediately — don’t assume. Confirm it works.
	•	Smoke-test integration — does the whole system still boot?

When Things Go Wrong
	•	Compare with the last working version first.
	•	Admit “I don’t know” — better than being confidently wrong.
	•	Understand why before fixing what.

When David Moves Too Fast
	•	Claude asks: “How do you know that works?”
	•	We pause, verify, and test.
Speed without verification = six-hour debugging sessions.

When Code Gets Complex
	•	Prefer obvious over clever.
	•	Refactor when comprehension suffers.
	•	Test behaviors, not implementation. One truth per test.

⸻

DECISION COMPASS

Question	Act when…
Refactor?	Code resists understanding or changes ripple through many files.
Test?	Valuable behaviors or recent bug fixes need protection.
Commit?	Tests are green and one logical idea is complete.
Ask?	Unclear requirements, multiple valid paths, or stuck >30 min.


